1 About

This document is a quick view on the ancestry data generated in the COPDgene project by running LAMP.

Some questions of the interest include:

  • What is the total number of local ancestry segments?
    • Remember that the number of SNPs is around 500K.
    • The number of segments reported in (Parker et al. 2014) is 38,566.
  • How long are these segments?
  • By doing a PCA model
    • Is PC1 all about the vector of global ancestry?
    • Are the other PCs (2, 3, …) are meaningful?

1.1 Updates

(1.1 @ March 6, 2017)

  • PCA is computed for covariance matrix among variables (not individuals)
    • For such a high-dimensional problem (~10K variables), random PCA (rPCA) algorithm is used.
    • As a result, PC1 now matches almost extacly to the global ancestry vector, while the other PCs seem to be just noise.
  • Association results in (Parker et al. 2014) were replicated
    • The original analysis is different from what is presented here.
      • 4 PCs were used to correct for population structure.
      • The ancestry segments were likely computed differently.
  • If FEV1_FVC_utah is transformed by inverse-normal, then the top association signal at Chr. 12 disapears.

2 Computation of ancestry segments

2.1 Input data

Input data is a table of 608,917columns (the number of SNPs) and 3,300 rows (the number of individals).

This table was produced from the LAMP output by a custom perl script. It was needed to compute GWAS in COPDgene admixed population within correction by local ancestry per SNP.

A sample of data for first 5 individuals and first 5 SNPs:

> acs[1:5, 1:5]

3 Load pre-computed data

annot <- copdgene_annot_acs()
acsg <- copdgene_acs_global()

acsg <- mutate(acsg, 
  acs_gr = cut(acs_global, breaks = c(0, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 1)))

Two variables are used from the acsg table:

  • acs_global: a continious measure of global ancestry (range from 0 to 1)
  • acs_gr: a factor variable with 4 levels (user here to plot nice figures)

5 Annotation for local ancestry

Fields in the annotation table:

  • acs: ID name of the ancestry segment
  • chr: Cromosome (1-22)
  • num_snps: the number of snps in a segment
  • num_ind_diff: the number of individuals that are different when comparing the current and the next ancestry segments
    • NA values mean that that segment was the last in Chromosome
  • length_bp: the length of segment measured in bp
  • length_cM: the length of segment measured in cM (converted from bp by simply dividing by 1M)

6 PCA model on local ancestry

A few notes on how PCA was computed:

  • A subset of ancestry segements was used: the length of segment > 10kb
    • The total number of segments available for the PCA analysis: 35,783
  • As the number of variables was 35,783, we used the random PCA (rPCA) algorithm implemented in the rsvd R package.
    • We estimated only the first 10 eigen vectors.

The R code is given below.

library(rsvd)

acs <- copdgene_acs(acs_size = 10e3)

acs_c <- scale(acs, center = T, scale = F)

mod <- rsvd(acs_c, k = 10)

ev <- mod$v
scores <- mod$u %*% diag(mod$d)

varexp <- mod$d^2 / sum(mod$d^2)

6.1 Explained variance

The total variance was approximated by the first 10 PCs.

7 Ancestry association mapping to replicate 12q14.1 locus

(Parker et al. 2014) conducted genome-wide association analysis for FEV1/FVC phenotype using 38,566 ancestry segments. The genome-wide significant signal was established at 12q14.1 locus, P = 2.1e-6.

Additionally, the same association analysis on FEV1pp phenotype showed genome-wide suggestive signal at the same Chr. 12, P = 1.3e-4.

The next fine-mapping analysis using genotype data revealed the most significant SNP rs348644, P = 1.76e-6.

The association results pointed at FAM19A2 gene:

  • Start: 61,708,248 bp from pter
  • End: 62,279,150 bp from pter
  • Size: 570,903 bases

Both phenotypes were corrected by covariates, including:

  • Age_Enroll + gender + BMI + ATS_PackYears + SmokCigNow
  • Global ancestry acs_global
  • Population structure
    • Parker2014: 4 PCs
      • These 4 PCs would be relevant for analysis of the whole sample, but the question is: whether this corection is relevant for a subset of 3,300 African-Americans.
    • Our analysis: no any PCs (genotype data not available)
      • However, we used the acs_global covariate, that will capture that part of population structure related to the african-europenean ancestry.

7.1 Base model for association analysis

mod1 <- lm(FEV1_FVC_utah ~ Age_Enroll + gender + BMI + 
  ATS_PackYears + SmokCigNow + acs_global, phen)

mod2 <- lm(FEV1pp_utah ~ Age_Enroll + gender + BMI + 
  ATS_PackYears + SmokCigNow + acs_global, phen)

7.3 Additional association mapping

Given that residuals in the FEV1_FVC_utah model showed a deviation from the normal distribution, we transformed FEV1_FVC_utah by inverse-normal and conducted the association mapping again.

We found the the top signal has a lower p-value 3.1e-05, while the p-value for untransformed phenotype in the original study was 2.1e-6.

7.4 Summary

Summary on ancestry association mapping results for FEV1-FVC in two studes, (Parker et al. 2014) and presented here.

Study Phenotype Top signal P-value #tests Corrected P-value
(Parker et al. 2014) FEV1-FVC 12q14.1 2.1e-6 38,566 0.08
Here FEV1-FVC chr12acs104145 3.3e-06 37,194 0.12
Here inormal FEV1-FVC chr12acs104145 3.2e-05 37,194 1
